### Reading Console Input

Use `stdin.readLineSync()` from the `dart:io` library to read user input from the console.

```dart
import 'dart:io';

void main() {
  stdout.write('Enter your name: ');
  String? name = stdin.readLineSync();

  print('Hello, $name!');
}
```

### Reading Numbers

Input is always read as a string. Convert it to the appropriate numeric type.

```dart
import 'dart:io';

void main() {
  stdout.write('Enter your age: ');
  String? input = stdin.readLineSync();

  if (input != null && input.isNotEmpty) {
    int age = int.parse(input);
    print('You are $age years old');
  }
}
```

### Safe Input Parsing

```dart
import 'dart:io';

void main() {
  stdout.write('Enter a number: ');
  String? input = stdin.readLineSync();

  if (input != null) {
    int? number = int.tryParse(input);
    if (number != null) {
      print('You entered: $number');
    } else {
      print('Invalid number');
    }
  }
}
```

### Input with Prompts

```dart
import 'dart:io';

String prompt(String message) {
  stdout.write(message);
  String? input = stdin.readLineSync();
  return input ?? '';
}

void main() {
  String name = prompt('Enter name: ');
  String ageStr = prompt('Enter age: ');
  int age = int.tryParse(ageStr) ?? 0;

  print('$name is $age years old');
}
```

> **Key Point:** `stdin.readLineSync()` returns `String?` (nullable). Always handle the null case. Use `int.tryParse()` for safer number conversion instead of `int.parse()`.

